					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">On the NES, each palette entry of the 2 x 4 on-screen palettes takes one byte, i.e. each palette entry can have a value of 0-255.<br /><br />So, is there a technical reason why the total number of colors on the NES is only 64 (52 + a few black entries) instead of 256?<br /><br />I would understand it if the palettes occupied only 24 bytes (6 bits for each of the 2 x 4 x 4 entries). But they take the full 32 bytes (8 bits for each of the 2 x 4 x 4 entries).</div>

					
